            <div class="mainBodyTextTop">
                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">discussion title:</div><div class="textLeft1"><span class="fs10">&nbsp; Communion/Lord's Supper/Eucharist, etc </span></div></div>
                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">emoticon:</div><div class="textLeft"><span class="fs11">&nbsp;<img src="http://acx.prospero.com/dir-app/icon.aspx?realmId=185&iconTypeId=2&iconName=32" border=0 height=15 width=15 align=texttop alt="Emoticon"></span></div></div>
                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">message #:</div><div class="textLeft"><span class="fs11">&nbsp; 975.1 </span></div></div>


                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">from:</div><div class="textLeft"><span class="fs11">&nbsp; <a class="memname" href="/dir-app/bbcard/profile.asp?webtag=iv-pplibchrist&uid=369381505" onClick="return LBB(369381505);">trudyj</a> <nobr></nobr></span></div></div>
                
                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">date:</div><div class="textLeft"><span class="fs11">&nbsp; 7/11/2003 7:31 pm</span></div></div>
                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">replies:</div><div class="textLeft"><span class="fs11">&nbsp; 5</span></div></div>
            </div><!-- End: mainBodyTextTop -->

            <br clear="all" />

            <div class="mainBodyText">
                <span class="fs5">As I sat through my church's communion service last week and contrasted it with the service I attended at the cathedral of St. John the Divine on Pentecost Sunday in New York, I was musing about this central rite of the Christian church and the different ways it is celebrated in different churches.  I'm not so interested in the theology--e.g. transubstantiation, Real Presence vs symbol--as in the logistics: when, where, how, what? (I have my own understanding of why which works for me, but I see all these others as being negotiable and am interested in the differences).

<P>In my church, we celebrate communion only four times a year, once a quarter.  Not associated with any holidays or holy days, just four Sabbaths roughly three months apart. It is a major service which usually takes much longer than a regular service.

<P>First, the pastor's sermon (or sermonette if he is merciful) is always related to something about Communion, to set the tone.  Then we all go downstairs and wash each other's feet, usually with men in one half of the auditorium and women in the other.  The ideal is to wash the feet of someone with whom you need to make amends, but more often people go for a newcomer or visitor, someone they don't know well or want to be particularly nice to. Or occasionally just a relative or close friend.

<P>Then we all come back upstairs and sit in every other pew. The pastor and two elders (ideally, if we have two ordained elders on hand) sit up front with the bread and &quot;wine&quot; (the wine is grape juice, served in little individual shot glasses). The pastor or an elder reads the passage about bread from 1 Corinthians 11, and then the deacons move out and start passing out bread to people.  While they do this, members of the congregation can stand and give a testimony about something they are thankful for, something God has done in their lives, etc. When everyone has the bread the pastor says a prayer and we all eat our piece.  Then ditto happens for the grape juice, with more testimonies again when the glasses are being collected (this is the only part I don't like: the little clinks are very distracting).

<P>As you might imagine, this all takes a very long time, which is why the service is so long, and I assume this, rather than any major theological reason, is why we do it so infrequently.  

<P>Anyway, after a lifetime of reading and being inspired by Anglican writers (most recently Nora Gallagher) on the beauty of the Eucharist and how meaningful it is (and comments from my friend who's recently turned Anglican about how important to him it is to receive communion every week), I thought, Yes, we should be doing this more often.  This is such a central part of the Christian life, it shouldn't just be an occasional thing.  But when comparing the two services mentioned above, mine and the Anglican one in NYC, I have to admit (and it may just be a matter of familiarity) that I LOVE the slow-paced, thoughtful way we do it.  Being moved up the aisle, to the altar, past the elements and back to the pew makes me feel like I'm on an assembly line (I realize St. John the Divine, being a HUGE church on a major Sunday, may have been more of an assembly line than most, but I have had the same feeling at other Anglican services).  I like the meditativeness of being able to sit in my pew, have it all brought to me, reflect and chew and swallow at my own pace.  And I do like the footwashing although I realize you couldn't practically do it every week.  My dad always points out that Jesus never meant &quot;wash each other's feet&quot; literally but that we should do humble acts of service for one another, and that we should do something practical like shine each other's shoes.  But I do like the archaic awkwardness of washing another person's feet.  It really does feel humble and servantlike although it's purely symbolic (nobody comes with dirty feet).

<P>There's also the little matter of wafer quality. Are all Anglican wafers as tasteless and melt-in-your mouth as the ones I got in NYC? It was gone before I got back to my seat without even the ghost of a taste to haunt me.  Ours are unleavened but very whole-grainy and chewy.  You have time to think &quot;This...is...my...body...which...was...broken...for...you&quot; before it's all gone.  And of course there's the whole grapejuice vs wine thing, which I realize depends on how strong a tradition of teetotalling your church has, but it's always a shock to me to taste alcohol in church.  

<P>Again, it's largely a matter of what's familiar I guess.  Which may make this rather a frivolous thread, but I'm interested in the differences in how different denominations and congregations do this, and why, and what's meaningful to you about it.  Interestingly the only other church I've attended much of besides my own and the Anglican, which is the Salvation Army, doesn't do communion at all--nor baptism--which makes them very odd fish for Christians.  Apparently the no-communion thing stems from Wm Booth working with alcoholics on the streets of London and not wanting to tempt them with the taste of alcohol, but I'm not sure that explanation really washes as Booth was post-Wesleyan and I think the Methodists were already well into the grape juice thing by that time.

<P>But I digress! Talk to me, talk to me about your experience of communion, eucharist, the Lord's Supper, mass, call it what you will!

<P>tj
<BR></span>
