        <div class="dBoxMain">
            <div class="mainBodyTextTop">
                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">re:</div><div class="textLeft1"><span class="fs10">&nbsp; Communion/Lord's Supper/Eucharist, etc </span></div></div>
                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">emoticon:</div><div class="textLeft"><span class="fs11">&nbsp;<img src="http://acx.prospero.com/dir-app/icon.aspx?realmId=185&iconTypeId=2&iconName=0" border=0 height=15 width=15 align=texttop alt="Emoticon"></span></div></div>
                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">message #:</div><div class="textLeft"><span class="fs11">&nbsp; 975.2 in response to <a href="message.asp?webtag=iv-pplibchrist&msg=975.1" target=_self>975.1</a></span></div></div>


                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">from:</div><div class="textLeft"><span class="fs11">&nbsp; <a class="memname" href="/dir-app/bbcard/profile.asp?webtag=iv-pplibchrist&uid=369383651" onClick="return LBB(369383651);">pmclean</a> <nobr>&nbsp;<img src="http://acx.prospero.com/dir-app/icon.aspx?realmId=185&iconTypeId=1&iconName=cl" border=0 height=15 width=15 align=texttop alt='Member Icon'></nobr></span></div></div>
                
                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">to:</div><div class="textLeft"><span class="fs11">&nbsp; <a class="memname" href="/dir-app/bbcard/profile.asp?webtag=iv-pplibchrist&uid=369381505" onClick="return LBB(369381505);">trudyj</a> <nobr></nobr></span></div></div>
                
                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">date:</div><div class="textLeft"><span class="fs11">&nbsp; 7/12/2003 6:44 pm</span></div></div>
                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">replies:</div><div class="textLeft"><span class="fs11">&nbsp; 5</span></div></div>
            </div><!-- End: mainBodyTextTop -->

            <br clear="all" />

            <div class="mainBodyText">
                <span class="fs5">Okay, you asked, I rambled. This is very long. &quot;My&quot; church has had so many different ways of doing things!

<P>In the church I first attended in the 1970's (pre liturgical-reform), communion was held once a month except in the Summer or when some other consideration intervened. Very often it did, so the frequency was more like four to six times a year. The main Sunday service was Morning Prayer. It was read from the 1662 prayerbook, and the psalms, canticles, creed, intercessions and Lords Prayer were all sung as corporate plainchant. A Morning Prayer service lasted about an hour.

<P>The communion services were very similar except they start on page 67 instead of page 4. Instead of canticles, we sang the decalogue, and the Gospel was preceeded and followed by a chanted proclaimation (which does not occur at Morning Prayer). After the sermon (which for practical purposes is the end of Morning Prayer) there would be an offertory procession, as robed acolytes brought up the people's offerings, and uncovered the hosts and wine on the altar. Then we would all kneel, while the priest sang the Sursum Corda in Sarum plainsong (which is stylisticly different from plainchant, but impossible to explain over the internet). He (always &quot;he&quot; -- this was prior to the ordination of the second Anglican woman priest) would then recite the Prayer of consecration with the congregation still kneeling, and would communicate himself. He would then serve communion to the acolytes and deacons while the choir sang the chang &quot;Agnus Dei&quot;. Then the choir would come up to the altar to communicate. When they went back, one choir member always remained kneeling in the center, as a marker between the two sides of the church who each communicated on their own side of the altar rail. Starting with the front row, people left their pews by the centre aisle, walked up to the altar-rail, knelt. When the rail  was full, the priest would pass along it, placing the bread into the precisely-cupped hands of each communicant to the words &quot;The Body of Our Lord Jesus Christ which was given for thee, preserve thy body and soul to everlasting life. Take and eat this in remembrance that Christ Jesus died for thee, and feed on him in thy heart, with thanksgiving&quot;. The deacon followed him serving the wine from a common chalice with the words &quot;The Blood of our Lord Jesus Christ which was shed for thee, preserve thy body and soul to everlasting life. Drink this, all of ye, in remembrance that Christ's Blood was shed for thee, and be thankful.&quot; Each person grasped the chalice in the precisely correct way. When each person has received both bread and wine, she would stand and return to her pew by the side aisle, and kneel until everyone has communicated.  Throughout the communion, the choir sang anthems in four- and six-part harmony. They would fall silent while the priest performed the ablutions after communion; then their last anthem would be the most ornate, after everyone had returned to their pews. Then there would be more chants -- the Lord's Prayer a second time to a different chant mode, a Thanksgiving, the Gloria, and the Peace blessing followed by a four-fold chanted Amen. Everything was slow, venerable and ornate: the Elizabethan language, the ancient music, the rich embroidered robes and heavy richly decorated platen and chalice.  Although we cycled past the altar, it never felt remotely like an assembly line, and the long kneeling vigil before and after your turn to go up left you plenty of time to meditate. This all took about ninety minutes.

<P>Liturgical reform brought us more frequent communion (typically every second Sunday) and alternation between the Traditional rite and various experimental rites. We were experimenting with ecumenism, too, so I attended Roman Catholic and United eucharists. So much is a matter of &quot;what you're used to&quot;: the RC's were beginning to take communion in the hand but without kneeling down and without sharing the cup. To me that seemed demeaning and assembly-line, and it certainly is very much quicker than kneeling in turn (which is *not* a virtue, from my perspective). The United Church used cubes of store-bought white bread and little inch-high paper cups of grape juice, passed around on a tray. Each person took one of each, and passed on the tray. Then the minister said a prayer, and everyone ate together. White-bread made me think, irreverantly, &quot;how appropriate&quot; and the purple grape juice made me think of the infamous grape koolaid of the same era. 

<P>Anglican contemporary rite follow largely the same pattern as the traditional rites. The language is no longer Elizabethan, and the robes and hangings were more typically ethnic embroidery, funky applique, or homespun and batik. The silver platen and chalice were replaced by earthy pottery. The liturgical prayers became said (because chant music hadn't been written yet for the new language) and &quot;folk hymns&quot; with acoustic guitars replaced the organ music. Some of what we did in those days was deep and meaningful: the eucharist became &quot;ours&quot;; the new trappings were still of the highest quality and steeped in meaning; in some aspects old meaningless customs were stripped away to reveal the purity of the underlying tradition. The return to weekly communion, with Morning Prayer as a *daily* office, is an example of such a change. The procession of the bread and wine by the laity is another example: instead of keeping the bread and wine in the sacristy, it is brought up ahead of the money gifts -- taking the emphasis off the offering of money, and underscoring the role of the laity in the eucharist. Often now, the bread brought up is home-baked -- a definate improvement over the pressed-cardboard wavers -- or whole-wheat wafers are used (so no, they're not *all* the same horrid white pasteboard).

<P>Some of what we did in those days was shoddy, and lost the dignity and contemplative tone of the older service. Some churches met change with reactionary responses: either returning to the Elizabethan language exclusively and trying to ignore the women priests and bishops, twentieth-century music, cutting-edge Bible scholarship, and other forces of change; or pushing change even further, altering the fundamental form of the eucharist, inventing new creeds and introducing non-Biblical liturgical texts, bringing electric guitars, drum-kits and keyboards into the sanctuary and replacing the choir anthems with performance-style praise-and-worship music. Because the traditional service is inherently slow, quiet and dignified; the typical &quot;contemporary&quot; service ends up being more of the, uh, &quot;exuberant&quot; style. The contemporary liturgy *can* be done in a contemplative style, but it rarely is. 

<P>The CCM church we now attend is a very exuberant style. Even though we have Eucharist every week, I find it less rewarding than the oldstyle occasional service. The long prayerful silence during the eucharist is eroded by the upbeat music; and after a half-hour or more of praise-and-worship music, the actual consecration and communion nearly get lost. In our Lutheran church, before we began our CCM sojourn with the local Anglican congregation, we had eucharist only twice a month. The music, although still praise-and-worship rock, was not as greatly amplified and was a slightly folksier style. Even so, the eucharist often got lost, largely because the priest never used a full prayer of consecration but only the minimal words of institution. Some Lutheran pastors insist on this minimal consecration because the rest of the prayer of consecration is non-biblical and therefor idolatrous. People who know our pastor better than I tell me his reason for using it was to get us out the door in under an hour. 

<P>Like the Anglican church, the Lutheran practice is for communicants to go up to the altar rail, kneel, and receive there; then return to their pews. Our church always used a fresh loaf from the Italian bakery: crusty and chewy. Afterward, the leftovers were set out with the coffee-hour refreshments, and any left after that was tossed in the trash. I've seen people slather butter onto the consecrated bread to have it with their coffee. That appals me. We didn't use the common cup, but were each handed a glass thimbleful to drain at the altar and then drop into a basket carried for the purpose by an acolyte who followed the minister. Thimbles contained either wine or grape-juice, and you could choose which you wanted. In another Lutheran church we attended, that had a circular central chancel, we stood (rather than kneeling) around the altar. You could take the wine from a common cup, but it had a pour-spout on the side so that you could have an individual glass if you wanted. Glass thimbles of grape juice were also carried around for those who didn't want wine -- *three* choices. In other Lutheran churches, you carry away your little glass and place it on trays located by the side-aisle for that purpose, or there are trays built onto the back of the altar-rail: you take a clean cup from the right, the minister pours wine or grape-juice into it, and when you have drunk you stack the dirty cups on the left. As a newcomer or visitor, you'll want to take careful note of whether the clean cups are right or left, and whether it's the clean ones or the dirty ones that are upside down. I find having to figure things like that out gets in the way of a prayerful communion, but of course only visitors have that problem.

<P>The best liturgical communions are at monasteries. Nothing is rushed or loud. Everyone knows their part, after the first day or so there's nothing to figure out. Often, communion is daily, but so deep and quiet that the whole day leading to it and from it just seems to be an adjunct to the eucharist. And then, the retreat ends and you have to go deal with real life again!</span>
                <table><tr></tr></table>
            </div>

