            <br clear="all" />

            <div class="mainBodyText">
                <span class="fs5">I'm still reeling from what Pamela said about the consecrated host being tossed into the trash, so forgive me if I stumble a bit and don't make much sense.  That would never have been allowed in either parish I've been active in!  Ugh!  Leftovers have to be eaten.  It is acceptable however, for crumbs to be set out for the birds, since they're also God's creatures.

<P>The parish I grew up in was led by a former Roman Catholic priest, and to this day I don't know how much of what he taught me was Episcopalian and how much was Roman Catholic. LOL  It was a very traditional church that loved Rite I with it's beautiful old language and didn't take well to the more contemporary language of Rite II, even though it was still treated the same.  Same slow, dignified service, same organ music.  Ahhhh, those were the good ol' days.  Father Frank was assisted by an acolyte (for several years that was me) except for passing the chalice.  We used a common cup, real wine (usually a strong Hearty Burgundy; Father Frank wanted you to literally *feel* the blood of Christ! LOL) and went to the altar to receive.  He taught that Communion should ideally be received every day, but once a week would suffice.  As for those leftovers I referred to above, I remember clearly being fed leftover host by the handful! LOL

<P>The parish (technically mission) that we most recently were active in did things basically the same way except for no acolytes, and the Deacon acted as chalice-bearer.

<P>~Jodi

<P></span>
