        <div class="dBoxMain">
            <div class="mainBodyTextTop">
                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">re:</div><div class="textLeft1"><span class="fs10">&nbsp; Communion/Lord's Supper/Eucharist, etc </span></div></div>
                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">emoticon:</div><div class="textLeft"><span class="fs11">&nbsp;<img src="http://acx.prospero.com/dir-app/icon.aspx?realmId=185&iconTypeId=2&iconName=0" border=0 height=15 width=15 align=texttop alt="Emoticon"></span></div></div>
                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">message #:</div><div class="textLeft"><span class="fs11">&nbsp; 975.4 in response to <a href="message.asp?webtag=iv-pplibchrist&msg=975.1" target=_self>975.1</a></span></div></div>


                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">from:</div><div class="textLeft"><span class="fs11">&nbsp; <a class="memname" href="/dir-app/bbcard/profile.asp?webtag=iv-pplibchrist&uid=369385549" onClick="return LBB(369385549);">sara_k</a> <nobr></nobr></span></div></div>
                
                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">to:</div><div class="textLeft"><span class="fs11">&nbsp; <a class="memname" href="/dir-app/bbcard/profile.asp?webtag=iv-pplibchrist&uid=369381505" onClick="return LBB(369381505);">trudyj</a> <nobr></nobr></span></div></div>
                
                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">date:</div><div class="textLeft"><span class="fs11">&nbsp; 7/14/2003 6:57 pm</span></div></div>
                <div class="oneLine"><div class="boldText">replies:</div><div class="textLeft"><span class="fs11">&nbsp; 5</span></div></div>
            </div><!-- End: mainBodyTextTop -->

            <br clear="all" />

            <div class="mainBodyText">
                <span class="fs5">I have a varied communion experience.

<P>I have had communion with my family, on a mountain ridge, that consisted of homemade wheat bread and grape juice taken with prayer and a mix of Gujurati and Hindi choruses, Youth For Christ songs, and hymns.

<P>I wasn't allowed communion in the Baptist Church (celebrated once a month) because I was not baptized.

<P>In later churches of various denominations, communion was once a month. It was made with little pillows of cracker and purple grape juice. LEading up to the communion was a set of prayers and Bible readings which emphasized that we must take communion with clean hearts and intentions or else the wrath of God would be upon us. The elders passed trays of crackers which we held and took together with the statement &quot;Do this in remembrance of me.&quot; Any child could take communion if their parents thought they were ready. I often didn't take communion even when I was in high school because I worried that my heart was not clear. Then the elders passed trays of glasses with grape juice and we drank the juice all together at the statement. Cups went in little holders in each pew. Then hymns were sung while we filed quietly out of the building.

<P>In my current church, there is a service every day but no longer communion every day (though if people come to the service it may be offered); 2 days a week there is Morning Prayer instead. M-Saturday (and Sunday at 8am) the service is &quot;low mass&quot;. There is communion but the whole service is spoken (not sung) and there is no choir or organ. The service lasts about an hour if there is a sermon. Sunday at 10am the service lasts 1.5-2 hours (less in summer or if a visiting priest is in charge).

<P>I usually go to 10 service. I like to sit in the back but my kids like the front - this makes a difference to mediation time. In front I get plenty of after meditation time but in the back I get some before and some after. After the sermon, Nicene Creed, Prayers of the people, confess our sins, pass the Peace, and announcements, two members of the congregation take the bread and wine up to the altar. The ushers collect the offerings and take them to the altar where all three offerings are blessed. The ushers and element bearers return to their seats, closing the altar rail behind them. We say the Great Thanksgiving, sing &quot;Holy&quot;. The priest consecrates the bread and wine; this is done is a sure and reverential way, taking time but not dragging on. The words are clear to everyone in the church. We say the Lord's Prayer, we sing Agnus Dei. We say both &quot;Christ our Passover is sacrificed for us; therefore let us keep the feast&quot; and &quot;Lord, I am not worthy that thou shouldst come under my roof but speak the word only and my soul shall be healed.&quot; The choir sings a last verse or two of psalm and then comes forward to receive as the priest has communion and gives it to the servers. After the choir we go up and kneel along the altar rail. After the choir receives, they sing an anthem (never bouncy). We may kneel or stand, we may receive in our hands or on our tongues. The wine is in two cups and one may guide the cup with one hand or touch the cup with one hand and not take the wine. The communion sentence ocassionaly changes. We return to our seats and kneel or sit. There is a communion hymn. The ushers withdraw the altar rail. We pray our thanksgiving. The priest gives a blessing. **At this point we used to have another Bible reading called &quot;The Second Gospel&quot; which was from John 1:1 but that has been removed over the last few years because people felt it made the service too long. &lt;rolls eyes&gt; We sing another hymn as the Priest and servers recess. We kneel and pray as the servers return to the sacristy.

<P>Sara</span>
